<subSubSection id="CCFD0CC3FFE8015463A5F1BE924088B7" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="84585F48FFE8015463A5F1BE92398977" blockId="10.[151,760,446,917]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="B693835AFFE8015463A5F1BE926D8AF7" bold="true" box="[151,284,446,469]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Comments.</emphasis>
The species was unknown to subsequent specialists and was mentioned only in catalogues. 
<bibRefCitation id="E07622B9FFE801546185F1DE93AE8937" author="WEISE J." editor="SCHENKLING S." firstAuthor="WEISE" journalOrPublisher="Berlin" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" pagination="1 - 225" refId="ref33576" refString="WEISE J. 1924: Pars 78: Chrysomelidae: 13. Galerucinae. In: SCHENKLING S. (ed.): Coleopterorum Catalogus. W. Junk, Berlin, pp. 1 - 225." title="Pars 78: Chrysomelidae: 13. Galerucinae" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Coleopterorum Catalogus" year="1924">WEISE (1924)</bibRefCitation>
listed it as 
<taxonomicName id="43E724CBFFE801546250F1FE91C58937" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1899" box="[354,692,510,533]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyxantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coxalis" subGenus="Haplotes">
<emphasis id="B693835AFFE801546250F1FE92928937" box="[354,483,510,533]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Platyxantha</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B693835AFFE8015462C7F1FE91248937" box="[501,597,510,533]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Haplotes</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B693835AFFE80154615AF1FE91C58937" box="[616,692,510,533]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">coxalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
while 
<bibRefCitation id="E07622B9FFE8015463A5F21E924E8917" author="WILCOX J. A." box="[151,319,542,565]" editor="WILCOX J. A." firstAuthor="WILCOX" journalOrPublisher="Editio seconda. W. Junk, ' s-Gravenhage" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" pagination="433 - 664" refId="ref33616" refString="WILCOX J. A. 1973: Chrysomelidae: Galerucinae: Luperini: Luperina. In: WILCOX J. A. (ed.): Coleopterorum Catalogus Supplementa. Pars 78 (3). Editio seconda. W. Junk, ' s-Gravenhage, pp. 433 - 664." title="Chrysomelidae: Galerucinae: Luperini: Luperina" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Coleopterorum Catalogus Supplementa. Pars 78 (3)." year="1973">WILCOX (1973)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="E07622B9FFE801546249F21E91508917" author="KIMOTO S." box="[379,545,542,565]" firstAuthor="KIMOTO" journalOrPublisher="Kurume University Journal" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" pagination="201 - 237" part="39" refId="ref31701" refString="KIMOTO S. 1990: Check-list of Chrysomelidae of south east Asia, south of Thailand and west of Irian-Jaya of Indonesia, VI. Galerucinae, 2. Kurume University Journal 39: 201 - 237." title="Check-list of Chrysomelidae of south east Asia, south of Thailand and west of Irian-Jaya of Indonesia, VI. Galerucinae, 2." type="journal article" year="1990">KIMOTO (1990)</bibRefCitation>
classified it in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="43E724CBFFE8015463EEF23E92308977" authorityName=", MOHAMEDSAID" authorityYear="1998" box="[220,321,574,597]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Polexima" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B693835AFFE8015463EEF23E92308977" box="[220,321,574,597]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Polexima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="84585F48FFE801546387F25E924088B7" blockId="10.[151,760,446,917]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">
In the BMNH I found two female 
<typeStatus id="5B5CE1EAFFE801546103F25E91FF8957" box="[561,654,606,629]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">syntypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="43E724CBFFE801546184F25E924789B7" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1899" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyxantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coxalis">
<emphasis id="B693835AFFE801546184F25E924789B7" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Platyxantha coxalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which do not correspond with Jacobyʼs description as he mentioned only males (
<bibRefCitation id="E07622B9FFE80154616FF29E919D8997" author="JACOBY M." box="[605,748,670,693]" firstAuthor="JACOBY" journalOrPublisher="Entomologische Zeitung (Stettin)" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" pagination="259 - 313" part="60" refId="ref31637" refString="JACOBY M. 1899: Descriptions of the new species of phytophagous Coleoptera obtained by Dr. Dohrn in Sumatra. Entomologische Zeitung (Stettin) 60: 259 - 313 + 1 pl." title="Descriptions of the new species of phytophagous Coleoptera obtained by Dr. Dohrn in Sumatra" type="journal article" year="1899">JACOBY 1899</bibRefCitation>
). In my opinion, this discrepancy can be easily explained by the structure of antennae. Both females have slightly thickened apical antennomeres (
<figureCitation id="1CDC43CDFFE8015462C0F2FE91308837" box="[498,577,766,789]" captionStart="Figs 94–104" captionStartId="20.[151,187,1619,1638]" captionTargetBox="[155,1436,190,1594]" captionTargetId="figure-13@20.[151,1437,190,1595]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs 94–104. Habitus of Taumacera. 94– T.variceps (Laboissière, 1933) (male); 95 – T.viridis (Hope, 1831) (male, syntype); 96 – T.coxalis (Jacoby, 1899) (female, syntype); 97 – T. jacobyi Weise, 1922 (male, syntype of Dorydea costatipennis Jacoby, 1896); 98 – T. javanensis Jacoby, 1895 (male, syntype); 99 – T. kinabaluensis (Mohamedsaid, 1995) (male); 100 – T. monstrosa (Jacoby, 1899) (male); 101 – T. multicostata (Jacoby, 1896) (female, syntype); 102 – T. submetallica (Jacoby, 1896) (female, syntype); 103 – T. sumatrana (Jacoby, 1899) (male); 104 – T. variabilis (Jacoby, 1891) (male, syntype)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4505540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4505540/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Fig. 96</figureCitation>
) which probably led Jacoby to treat them as males. Although the males are unknown to me I have no doubt that 
<taxonomicName id="43E724CBFFE801546116F33E91898877" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1899" box="[548,760,830,853]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyxantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coxalis">
<emphasis id="B693835AFFE801546116F33E91898877" box="[548,760,830,853]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Platyxantha coxalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="43E724CBFFE80154623DF35E92F78857" authorityName="Thunberg" authorityYear="1814" box="[271,390,862,885]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Taumacera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B693835AFFE80154623DF35E92F78857" box="[271,390,862,885]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Taumacera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on habitus and the absence of tibial spurs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
